				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varXi >1$$\end{document} and vice-versa, i.e., we approach the regime in which there is not coherent relaxation. It is very remarkable to see that by choosing the value suggested (Rauch and Tremaine 1996), we achieve the maximum of the EMRI rate curve. If the “real” value of Ξ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varXi $$\end{document} happened to be a factor 10 larger, then we would be drastically dropping the rates and increasing the direct plunges and, of course, also the tidal disruptions event rate, since these occur at larger radii.

